  sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > 'Red/red-manual/editing.html' &&
X<html>
X<head>
X<title>Red: Browsing and Editing</title>
X<link rev="made" href="mailto:mik@cs.su.oz.au">
X</head>
X
X<body bgcolor=white>
X
X<center>
X<table>
X<tr>
X	<td valign=top> <IMG SRC="red-logo.GIF" ALT="RED" > </td>
X	<td> <font size=+3>Efficient Browsing and Editing</font> </td>
X</tr>
X</table>
X</center>
X
X<hr>
X
X<h3>Moving the cursor</h3>
X
XBeing able to move the cursor around in the text easily and quickly and to
Xscan through a large document is important for convenient and efficient
Xediting.<p>
X
XIn Red, there are two basic alternatives to move the cursor: the mouse and the
Xkeyboard.  Using the mouse to move the cursor or to change the view is fairly
Xstraightforward, but nevertheless briefly explained in the section
X<A HREF="mouse.html">Using the mouse</A>.  This section explains the use of
Xkeys to move the cursor and the view and edit the text.<p>
X
XTwo groups of commands are available for wandering through a text: commands to
Xmove the <STRONG>cursor</STRONG> (the mark where text is entered) and commands
Xto move the <STRONG>view</STRONG>.  The view is the window showing the section
Xof the text you can see at any time.  If I say "the view is moved down", what
Xit means is, that the edit window will display a section of the text further
Xdown from before.<p>
X
XThe cursor and the view are losely connected.  The cursor never leaves the
Xview. So similar effects can often be achieved with cursor and view commands.
XMoving the cursor up in the text will take the view with it, and vice versa.
XBut, as you will see, there are some differences.<p>
X
XThe general rules are: When the cursor leaves the screen, the view is adjusted
Xto show the cursor in the middle of the screen.  When the view is changed so 
Xthat the cursor would disappear from the screen, the cursor is set to the very
Xtop or bottom of the view, depending on where it was before.<p>
X
XAlmost all of the cursor and view movements can be done with the cursor block
Xand the modifier keys.  In addition, some editing functions (deleting and 
Xcutting text) can be done with the cursor keys as well.  Getting familiar with
Xthe functions on the cursor keys is probably one of the most important things
Xfor efficient editing.<p>
X
XHere is a table listing the functions bound to the cursor keys:<p>
X
X<table border>
X<caption> <strong>Function bindings of Cursor Keys</strong> </caption>
X	<th>  <th>  <th>shift  <th>alt  <th>shift-alt  <th>ctrl  <th>shift-ctrl  <th>alt-ctrl 
X   <tr align=center>
X	<td><IMG WIDTH=32 HEIGHT=32 SRC="../graphics/buttons/right.gif" border=0>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#forward-char">forward-<br>char</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#end-of-line">end-of-<br>line</A> 
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#forward-word">forward-<br>word</A>
X	<td> 
X	<td> <A HREF="func-edit.html#delete-char">delete-char</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-edit.html#cut-to-end-of-line">cut-to-<br>end-of-line</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-edit.html#cut-to-end-of-word">cut-to-<br>end-of-word</A>
X   <tr align=center>
X
X	<td><IMG WIDTH=32 HEIGHT=32 SRC="../graphics/buttons/left.gif" border=0>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#backward-char">backward-<br>char</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#beginning-of-line">beginning-<br>of-line</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#backward-word">backward-<br>word</A>
X	<td> 
X	<td> <A HREF="func-edit.html#backward-delete-char">backward-<br>delete-char</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-edit.html#cut-line">cut-line</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-edit.html#cut-word">cut-word</A>
X   <tr align=center>
X
X	<td><IMG WIDTH=32 HEIGHT=32 SRC="../graphics/buttons/up.gif" border=0>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#previous-line">previous-<br>line</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#scroll-line-up">scroll-<br>line-up</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#previous-page">previous-<br>page</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#scroll-half-page-up">scroll-half-<br>page-up</A>
X	<td>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#beginning-of-text">beginning-<br>of-text</A>
X	<td>
X   <tr align=center>
X
X	<td><IMG WIDTH=32 HEIGHT=32 SRC="../graphics/buttons/down.gif" border=0>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#next-line">next-line</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#scroll-line-down">scroll-<br>line-down</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#next-page">next-<br>page</A>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#scroll-half-page-down">scroll-half-<br>page-down</A>
X	<td>
X	<td> <A HREF="func-move.html#end-of-text">end-of-text</A>
X	<td>
X</table>
X<p>
XApart from the cursor keys, there are some other keys that move the cursor
Xand perform basic editing functions.  They are listed in the following table.
X<p>
X
X<table border cellpadding=3>
X<caption> <strong>Other Cursor and Edit Keys</strong> </caption>
X	<th>Key Name  <th>Function called <tr>
X	<td><strong>Insert  <td><A HREF="func-edit.html#paste">paste</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>Backspace  <td><A HREF="func-edit.html#backward-delete-char">backward-delete-char</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>Delete  <td><A HREF="func-edit.html#delete-char">delete-char</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>Home  <td><A HREF="func-move.html#beginning-of-text">beginning-of-text</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>End  <td><A HREF="func-move.html#end-of-text">end-of-text</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>Page up  <td><A HREF="func-move.html#previous-page">previous-page</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>Page down  <td><A HREF="func-move.html#next-page">next-page</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>F2  <td><A HREF="func-edit.html#select-line">select-line</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>F3  <td><A HREF="func-edit.html#paste">paste</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>F4  <td><A HREF="func-edit.html#cut-line">cut-line</A> <tr>
X	<td><strong>F12  <td><A HREF="func-misc.html#undo">undo</A> <tr>
X</table>
X
X
X<h3>Line-Oriented Editing</h3>
X
XWhen writing program code, the text is often organised in lines.
XAs a result, the unit for editing (deleting, moving, copying) is
Xoften a line.<p>
X
XRed provides some functions for handling lines. They are <I>select-line, 
Xcut-line</I>, and <I>paste</I> and are by default bound to the function keys
X F2, F3 and F4 (see table above).<p>
X
XUsing these three keys, lines or groups of lines can be removed, copied,
Xor moved very quickly.  When selecting lines, the first call to 
X<I>select-line</I> will select the current line.  Every subsequent call will
X<I>add</I> the next line to the selection.  The selected text is 
Xautomatically put into the paste buffer (as it is the convention for 
XX-Windows applications).  No explicit copy operation is needed. (For more
Xdetails, see <a href="cut-paste.html">Cut, Copy and Paste</a>.)<p>
X
XSimilarly, when cutting lines (using <I>cut-line</I>), lines are collected 
Xin the paste buffer as long as no other functions are called inbetween.
X (That means: when doing a cut, then moving the cursor, then cut again, the
Xsecond cut will <I>replace</I> the first in the paste buffer.  But when
Xthe cut-functions are called consecutively, the second cut is <I>added</I>
Xto the paste buffer.)  This way, a group of lines can be moved (cut and 
Xpasted) quickly.
X
X<hr>
X  <A HREF="red-main-page.html">
X  <IMG SRC="../graphics/buttons/back.gif" border=0 align=middle >Main index</A>
X
X</body>
X</html>
SHAR_EOF
  $shar_touch -am 0512222696 'Red/red-manual/editing.html' &&
  chmod 0640 'Red/red-manual/editing.html' ||
  echo 'restore of Red/red-manual/editing.html failed'
  shar_count="`wc -c < 'Red/red-manual/editing.html'`"
  test 7006 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Red/red-manual/editing.html: original size 7006, current size $shar_count"
  rm -f _sharnew.tmp
fi
