# ============= Red/red-manual/find-replace.html ==============
if test -f 'Red/red-manual/find-replace.html' && test X"$1" != X"-c"; then
  echo 'x - skipping Red/red-manual/find-replace.html (file already exists)'
  rm -f _sharnew.tmp
else
  > _sharnew.tmp
  echo 'x - extracting Red/red-manual/find-replace.html (text)'
  sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > 'Red/red-manual/find-replace.html' &&
X<html>
X<head>
X<title>Red: Find and Replace</title>
X<link rev="made" href="mailto:mik@cs.su.oz.au">
X</head>
X
X<body bgcolor=white>
X
X<center>
X<table>
X<tr>
X	<td valign=top> <IMG SRC="red-logo.GIF" ALT="RED" > </td>
X	<td> <font size=+3>Find and Replace</font> </td>
X</tr>
X</table>
X</center>
X
X<hr>
X
XFive functions exist to find and replace text.  They are: <em>find, 
Xfind-backward, find-next, find-next-reverse</em> and <em>replace.  Find,
Xfind-backward</em> and <em>replace</em> open dialog boxes to let you specify
Xwhat to search for (and what to replace it with).  The <em>find-next</em>
Xfunctions can be used for two things: to repeat the last find operation
Xor to find the next occurence of a string visible on your screen. This will be 
Xexplained in more detail in the next section.
X
X<h2>Finding Text</h2>
X
X<h3>If you have the text on the screen...</h3>
X
XOften you want to find a string that you currently see on the screen (e.g.
Xyou see a procedure call and you want to find the procedure definition, or
Xyou see a variable and you wonder where else this variable is used).<p>
X
XA quick way exists to perform this find operation: the 
X<A HREF="func-misc.html#find-next">find-next</A> function.  (Follow this link 
Xto see how to call this function.)  If a selection is on, 
X<em>find-next</em> searches for the next occurence of the selected text.  Thus,
Xto find the next use of a variable, do the following:
X
X<ul>
X	<li>select the variable name (e.g. by double clicking on it,
X		see <A HREF="cut-paste.html#selections">How to make a 
X		selection</A> if you are not sure about this)
X	<li>call <em>find-next</em> (by either key, tool bar button or menu
X		button)
X</ul>
X
X<em>Find-next</em> uses the same find parameters (search direction: forward or
Xbackward, case sensitive or not, whole word only or not) as the last find
Xoperation (specified in the <em>find</em> dialog). The default (if you have not
Xused <em>find</em> yet) is forward, case insensitive, not only whole words.<p>
X
XYou can reverse the search direction by calling 
X<A HREF="func-misc.html#find-next-reverse">find-next-reverse</A> instead.  If,
Xfor instance, the current search direction is forward, 
X<em>find-next-reverse</em> will search for the current selection 
X<em>backwards</em>.
X
X<h4>Wrapping around</h4>
X
XIf you perform a find operation (e.g. forward) and the search string can not 
Xbe found between the cursor position and the end of the text, Red notifies you
Xwith a message in the information area.  If you then call find-next 
X<em>again</em>, it wraps around to the beginning of the text and continues the
Xsearch there (it notifies you of doing this with a message in the information 
Xarea).  The same principle applies when searching backwards.
X
X<h3>If you don't have the text on the screen...</h3>
X
XIf you want to search for a piece of text that you do not currently see on the
Xscreen (so you can not select it and call <em>find-next</em>), you use the 
X<A HREF="func-misc.html#find">find</A> function.  Follow this link to read
Xa description of the options and key bindings of <em>find</em>.<p>
X
X
X<strong> TO BE CONTINUED...</strong>
X
X<hr>
X  <A HREF="red-main-page.html">
X  <IMG SRC="../graphics/buttons/back.gif" border=0 align=middle >Main index</A>
X
X</body>
X</html>
SHAR_EOF
  $shar_touch -am 0512222696 'Red/red-manual/find-replace.html' &&
  chmod 0640 'Red/red-manual/find-replace.html' ||
  echo 'restore of Red/red-manual/find-replace.html failed'
  shar_count="`wc -c < 'Red/red-manual/find-replace.html'`"
  test 3247 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Red/red-manual/find-replace.html: original size 3247, current size $shar_count"
  rm -f _sharnew.tmp
fi
